<Content>Eat the bread and dunk the uncle Five of us went for a four day break to Bali and a friend recommended Villa Ixora as our launching pad during the stay. The hotel jeep drove us past paddy-fields and through the fleeting blessings of numerous water temples along the way. When we arrived, Villa Ixora, with its contrast of Balinese architecture and clean, modern interiors, amid a colorful landscaped garden, set the right mood for a great holiday.The owners, Helmut and Julia, showed us to our large bungalow with two bedrooms and two bathrooms, and a kitchen large enough to dance in. Loud screams woke me up next morning and I muttered to my husband, 鈥淔ine resort, this is.鈥?But it was my daughter, Alexandra, normally in need of resuscitation aid at an international level (try European dad and Asian mum) in the morning, but now already at the pool playing dunking with my brother, John. Later, we sat at the open thatched-roof pavilion by the pool, for an elaborate buffet and cooked breakfast with home baked (!) German and other tasty types of bread. Ever obliging, Julia took us downtown several times, even bringing us three girls - where else (?) 鈥?shopping (!!). The guys tagged along but found a cool beer more enticing than batik and handicraft. Coming home was simple and fast with cheap taxi rides 鈥?though we had to watch the zeroes in the rupiahs 鈥?so confusing to deal in millions! If only it were for real. They arranged a tour for us to Ubud and the surroundings, after instructing the driver where to bring us for sightseeing and lunch. The Ubud trip was a great experience with its breathtaking mountain views along the way and the unique Antonio Blanco museum 鈥?a huge bungalow and sprawling grounds all dedicated to the art of the Spanish artist.Too tired and lazy to go out some nights, we watched cable TV in the room, swam in the pool or surrendered to a Balinese massage, and ate at the pavilion where the menu was good and inexpensive 鈥?often cooked by Helmut himself. We volunteered as guinea pigs for Julia (though you can safely leave out the 鈥榞uinea鈥?. She makes and decorates weddings cakes for hotels and private parties, bakes bread and cookies 鈥?so we really pigged out. The service was impeccable throughout our stay 鈥?from the basics -tea and coffee making facilities in the room and cleanliness - to arranging massages, tours, taxis and, if we needed rupiahs or mangoes, the manageress, Titin, hopped on her scooter. Julia and Helmut -ex-globe trotting CEO, master of the art of entertainment, small talk or serious discussions on any subject, were always around to see to our needs or aches and pains. On the last evening, we mentioned sea food barbeque and before we knew it, someone had gone to buy fresh seafood and it was another night of practicing a happy Singaporean鈥檚 life philosophy at Helmut and Julia鈥檚 best. Hmm. Yummy! Do we really have to leave the next morning? And, oh yes, the birds in this paradise did get their chance to wake us up gently the other mornings. Alexandra had so much fun till late at night, she was back to her normal morning state of comatose 鈥榰nwakeability鈥?鈥?just in time for the start of school. 
